# 🚀 Day 23 – Designing the Data Model (The Brain of Your App)

Welcome to **Day 23**!

Yesterday, we designed **what the user sees** (the screens).

Today, we'll design **what the app stores**.

This is called the **Data Model**.

Don't worry—we are **not** writing SQL or database code today. We are thinking like architects.

---

# 🎯 Today's Goal

By the end of today, you'll know:

* What information your app needs to store
* How different pieces of information are connected
* How a real-world health app organizes data

---

# Think of the App as a Digital Hospital

Imagine you own a hospital.

What records would you keep?

At the highest level:

```text
Hospital
    │
    ├── Users
    ├── Patients
    ├── Blood Reports
    ├── AI Analyses
    └── Uploaded Files
```

These are the main "things" (called **entities**) in your app.

---

# Entity 1 – User

A user is the person who logs into the app.

Example:

```text
User

User ID: 1001
Name: Srujan
Email: srujan@email.com
Password: ********
Created On: 10-Jul-2026
```

One user can have many blood reports.

---

# Entity 2 – Blood Report

Every uploaded report becomes a record.

Example:

```text
Blood Report

Report ID: 501
Date: 10-Jul-2026
Hospital: Apollo
PDF File
OCR Status
```

A user can upload hundreds of reports.

---

# Entity 3 – Blood Test Values

Each report contains many values.

Example:

```text
Blood Test

Hemoglobin : 13.4
HbA1c : 5.6
Vitamin D : 31
Vitamin B12 : 540
WBC : 6800
Platelets : 250000
```

Think of this as the medical information extracted from the uploaded report.

---

# Entity 4 – AI Analysis

The app creates an explanation for every report.

Example:

```text
AI Analysis

Summary

Health Score

Suggestions

Warnings

Generated Date
```

Notice that the AI explanation is stored separately from the blood values.

---

# Entity 5 – Uploaded File

We also keep the original document.

Example:

```text
File

Original PDF

Upload Date

File Size

Storage Location
```

This lets users open the original report whenever they want.

---

# How Everything Connects

Here's the complete picture:

```text
User
 │
 ├── Report 1
 │      │
 │      ├── Original PDF
 │      ├── Blood Test Values
 │      └── AI Analysis
 │
 ├── Report 2
 │      │
 │      ├── Original PDF
 │      ├── Blood Test Values
 │      └── AI Analysis
 │
 └── Report 3
        │
        ├── Original PDF
        ├── Blood Test Values
        └── AI Analysis
```

This is much cleaner than storing everything in one huge object.

---

# Why Is This Important?

Imagine Alice uploads five reports.

You don't want this:

```text
Alice

Hemoglobin: 13.2
```

because it overwrites the old value.

Instead, you want:

```text
Alice

Report 1
Hemoglobin: 11.4

Report 2
Hemoglobin: 12.6

Report 3
Hemoglobin: 13.2
```

Now you can show trends over time.

---

# Data Flow in the App

When a user uploads a report:

```text
Upload PDF
      │
      ▼
Store Original File
      │
      ▼
OCR Reads Values
      │
      ▼
Save Blood Test Values
      │
      ▼
Generate AI Explanation
      │
      ▼
Save AI Analysis
      │
      ▼
Show Results to User
```

Every step creates data that can be used later.

---

# Real Example

Suppose you upload this report:

```text
Hemoglobin : 10.8
HbA1c : 6.7
Vitamin D : 18
```

The app stores:

**Original File**

* report_001.pdf

**Blood Values**

* Hemoglobin = 10.8
* HbA1c = 6.7
* Vitamin D = 18

**AI Analysis**

* Mild anemia detected.
* HbA1c suggests diabetes.
* Vitamin D deficiency present.

Later, if you upload another report, it becomes a **new report**, not an update to the old one.

